{"title_page": "Stephen McLaughlin", "text_new": "{{Distinguish|Steve McLaughlin}}\n{{short description|Irish footballer}}\n{{Lead too short|date=October 2014}}\n{{Use Irish English|date=August 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2013}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name              = Stephen McLaughlin\n| image             = \n| image_size        = \n| caption           = \n| fullname          = Stephen Antony McLaughlin<ref name=\"Professional retain list & free transfers 2012/13\">{{Cite news\n |title=Professional retain list & free transfers 2012/13\n |url=http://www.football-league.co.uk/staticFiles/4e/bd/0,,10794~179534,00.pdf\n |publisher=The Football League\n |format=PDF\n |date=18 May 2013\n |page=22\n |access-date=23 June 2013\n |url-status=dead\n |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140802074454/http://www.football-league.co.uk/staticFiles/4e/bd/0,,10794~179534,00.pdf\n |archive-date=2 August 2014\n}}</ref>\n| birth_date        = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1990|6|14}}<ref name=\"11v11\">{{cite web |url=https://www.11v11.com/players/stephen-mclaughlin-240484/ |title=Stephen McLaughlin|website=11v11.com |publisher=AFS Enterprises |accessdate=21 July 2018}}</ref>\n| birth_place       = [[County Donegal|Donegal]], Ireland\n| height            = {{height|m=1.78}}<ref name=\"11v11\"/>\n| position          = [[Midfield]]\n| clubnumber        = 11\n| youthyears1 = 2006\u20132008\n| youthclubs1 = Rashenny football club\n| years1 = 2008\u20132010\n|  clubs1 = [[Finn Harps F.C.|Finn Harps]]\n| caps1 = 48\n| goals1 = 2\n| years2 = 2011\u20132013\n|  clubs2 = [[Derry City F.C.|Derry City]]\n| caps2 = 57\n| goals2 = 13\n| years3 = 2013\u20132015\n|  clubs3 = [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]]\n| caps3 = 9\n| goals3 = 0\n| years4 = 2013\n|  clubs4 = \u2192 [[Bristol City F.C.|Bristol City]] (loan)\n| caps4 = 5\n| goals4 = 0\n| years5 = 2014\n|  clubs5 = \u2192 [[Notts County F.C.|Notts County]] (loan)\n| caps5 = 13\n| goals5 = 0\n| years6 = 2014\u20132015\n|  clubs6 = \u2192 [[Southend United F.C.|Southend United]] (loan)\n| caps6 = 6\n| goals6 = 1\n| years7 = 2015\u2013\n|  clubs7 = [[Southend United F.C.]]\n| caps7 = 152\n| goals7 = 19\n| club-update = 09:11, 11 March 2020 (UTC)\n}}\n'''Stephen Antony McLaughlin''' (born 14 June 1990) is an Irish [[Association football|footballer]] who plays for [[Football League One|League One]] side [[Southend United F.C.|Southend United]] as a [[Midfielder#Winger|winger]].\n\n==Career==\n\n===Early years===\nMcLaughlin began his career at his local club St. Mary's, and played all his under-age football for the club. In 2006, he signed for Clonmany Shamrocks senior side of the [[Inishowen Football League]], and was successful during his first spell in junior football. Stephan was close with a lad called dj mc geoghegan, the two were a strike force not to be messed with going threw the st Mary\u2019s academy, dj went on to be Stephan\u2019s best man at his wedding in 2018.\n\n===Finn Harps===\nAfter appearing in League and Cup finals for Clonmany, McLaughlin was signed by [[Finn Harps F.C.|Finn Harps]], and played for their Under 20 and A Championship sides upon arrival. He was then called into the first-team, and went on to play several games for the club in the 2008 season. He was then assigned the no. 7 jersey for the 2009 campaign, with manager James Gallagher using McLaughlin right across the midfield and front-line.He took his inspiration in football from his neighbour DJ Mcgeoghegan who in turn took his inspiration from local car dealer Liam.\n\n===Derry City===\nHe signed for [[Derry City F.C.|Derry City]] after the 2010 season, after impressing in games against Derry at both [[Finn Park]] and the [[Brandywell]]. The move was touted at the end of the season, with McLaughlin signing terms with [[Stephen Kenny (footballer)|Stephen Kenny]]'s side in January 2011.<ref>{{cite web\n|url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/irish/9313840.stm\n|title=Derry City sign Stephen McLaughlin from Finn Harps\n|accessdate=2013-01-03\n|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref> He wore the no. 15 shirt for the Candystripes. McLaughlin secured promotion from the [[League of Ireland First Division]] with the club in his first season, and won the [[FAI Cup]] in his second, netting 17 goals along the way.\n\n===Nottingham Forest===\nMcLaughlin signed with English Championship side [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]] on 3 January 2013,<ref>{{cite news|title=Reds Land Stephen|url=http://www.nottinghamforest.co.uk/news/article/reds-land-stephen-576973.aspx|work=nottinghamforest.co.uk|publisher=Nottingham Forest F.C.|date=3 January 2013|first=Fraser|last=Nicholson}}</ref> believed to be for a fee of roughly \u00a3160,000.{{citation needed|date=September 2013}} McLaughlin did not make an appearance during the remainder of the 2012\u201313 season. After a spell out on loan to [[Bristol City F.C.|Bristol City]] at the start of the 2013 season, McLaughlin made his full Forest debut against [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]] on 21 April 2014 under caretaker manager [[Gary Brazil]]. At the beginning of the [[2014\u201315 Nottingham Forest F.C. season|2014\u201315 season]] under [[Stuart Pearce]], McLaughlin became a more prominent member of the first team, with four appearances from the bench in [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Forest's]] first six games.<ref>{{cite web |title=Season Statistics |url=http://www.nottinghamforest.co.uk/team/stats_1314.aspx |publisher=Nottingham Forest F.C. |date=27 August 2014 |access-date=27 August 2014 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140924102900/http://www.nottinghamforest.co.uk/team/stats_1314.aspx |archive-date=24 September 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nAs appearances for the first team at Forest became increasingly limited, McLaughlin joined their local rivals [[Notts County F.C.|Notts County]] on a one-month emergency loan on 30 September 2014.<ref>{{cite web |title=Nottingham Forest loan Stephen McLaughlin to Notts County |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/29414034 |publisher=BBC Sport |date=30 September 2014 |accessdate=30 September 2014}}</ref>\n\n====Southend (loan)====\nAfter a spell back at Forest, McLaughlin signed with [[Southend United F.C.|Southend United]] until the end of the 2014\u201315 season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nottinghamforest.co.uk/news/article/mclaughlin-signs-for-southend-2361053.aspx|title=McLaughlin signs for Southend|publisher=|accessdate=21 November 2017}}</ref>\nHis debut for the Shrimpers was away at [[Bury F.C.|Bury]], however this lasted just six minutes as the game was abandoned due to torrential rain,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/31996809|title=Bury A-A Southend United|date=28 March 2015|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=21 November 2017}}</ref> and his next game was at home to [[Mansfield Town F.C.|Mansfield]] which Southend won 2\u20130, and McLaughlin played 87 minutes. He scored twice in his spell for the Shrimpers, the first was in a 2\u20130 win over [[Newport County A.F.C.|Newport]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/32199850|title=Southend United 2-0 Newport County|date=14 April 2015|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=21 November 2017}}</ref> and the second helped Southend to [[Wembley Stadium]] as he scored in extra time of the League 2 play-off semi-final against [[Stevenage F.C.|Stevenage]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/32620041|title=Southend United 3-1 Stevenage (agg 4-2)|date=14 May 2015|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=21 November 2017}}</ref> He went on to play an hour in the final against [[Wycombe Wanderers F.C.|Wycombe Wanderers]], which Southend eventually won 7\u20136 on penalties meaning that they won promotion to [[Football League One|League One]]. After that game McLaughlin's loan spell ended,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.southendunited.co.uk/news/article/southend-united-joe-pigott-jake-cassidy-stephen-mclaughlin-2472517.aspx|title=News: Loanees return to parent clubs - News - Southend United|publisher=Southend United F.C.|accessdate=21 November 2017}}</ref> although having been released by Nottingham Forest, he has been linked with a permanent move back to Southend.\n\n===Southend United===\nOn 27 August 2015, McLaughlin joined Southend United on a permanent deal, signing a two-year deal.<ref>{{cite web |title=Stephen McLaughlin joins Southend from Nottingham Forest |url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11716/9967570/stephen-mclaughlin-joins-southend-from-nottingham-forest |publisher=SkySports |date=27 August 2015 |accessdate=27 August 2015}}</ref> McLaughlin made his debut as a substitute against Coventry City on 31 August 2015. McLaughlin has had a rough time with injuries in his career. He still goes unnoticed from the fans for the impact that he made in the second play off leg against Stevenage. Scoring and setting up a goal. McLaughlin gives it his all every game.\n\n==Career statistics==\n{{updated|match played 16 September 2017}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|+Appearances and goals by club, season and competition\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!colspan=\"3\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|National Cup\n!colspan=\"2\"|League Cup\n!colspan=\"2\"|Other\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!Division!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[Finn Harps F.C.|Finn Harps]]\n|[[2011 League of Ireland|2009]]\n|[[League of Ireland]]\n|16||1||0||0||0||0||0||0||16||1\n|-\n|[[2010 League of Ireland|2010]]\n|League of Ireland\n|32||1||0||0||0||0||0||0||32||1\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n! 48 !! 2 !! 0 !! 0 !! 0 !! 0 !! 0 !! 0 !! 48 !! 2\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[Derry City F.C.|Derry City]]\n|[[2011 League of Ireland|2011]]\n|League of Ireland\n|33||3||0||0||3||3||0||0||36||6\n|-\n|[[2012 League of Ireland|2012]]\n|League of Ireland\n|24||10||5||2||2||0||7||3||38||15\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n! 57 !! 13 !! 5 !! 2 !! 5 !! 3