 1)'' in French at archive.org]]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080111053727/http://caricaturesetcaricature.over-blog.com/article-6400408.html Editorial cartoons of the Second Empire]\n* [http://www.computours.co.uk/beziers/place_de_la_revolution/ Place de la Revolution, B\u00e9ziers & Napoleon 111]\n* [http://omniatlas.com/maps/europe/18481219/ Maps of Europe covering the reign of Napoleon III (omniatlas)]\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-hou|[[House of Bonaparte]]}}\n{{s-break}}\n{{S-off|}}\n{{s-break}}\n{{S-bef|before=[[Louis-Eug\u00e8ne Cavaignac]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[President of the French Republic]]|years=20 December 1848 \u2013 2 December 1852}}\n{{s-vac|reason=[[Second French Empire|Empire]] declared|next=[[Adolphe Thiers]]}}\n{{s-break}}\n{{S-reg|}}\n{{s-break}}\n{{S-vac|last=[[Louis Philippe I]]|as=king|last2=[[Napoleon I]]=as emperor}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Emperor of the French]]|years=2 December 1852 \u2013 4 September 1870}}\n{{s-vac|reason=[[French Third Republic|Republic declared]]}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Bonaparte family}}\n{{Heads of state of France}}\n{{French Pretenders}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n\n[[Category:Napoleon III| ]]\n[[Category:19th-century Presidents of France]]\n[[Category:19th-century monarchs of France]]\n[[Category:19th-century Princes of Andorra]]\n[[Category:Bonapartist pretenders to the French throne]]\n[[Category:French emperors]]\n[[Category:House of Bonaparte]]\n[[Category:French people of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:People from Paris]]\n[[Category:French people of the Revolutions of 1848]]\n[[Category:French people of the Crimean War]]\n[[Category:French people of the Franco-Prussian War]]\n[[Category:French prisoners of war in the 19th century]]\n[[Category:Monarchs imprisoned and detained during war]]\n[[Category:1808 births]]\n[[Category:1873 deaths]]\n[[Category:Corsican politicians]]\n[[Category:Leaders who took power by coup]]\n[[Category:Deaths from sepsis]]\n[[Category:Infectious disease deaths in England]]\n[[Category:French Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:Princes of France (Bonaparte)]]\n[[Category:Napoleon]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic monarchs]]\n[[Category:French people of Corsican descent]]\n[[Category:Second French intervention in Mexico]]\n[[Category:Dethroned monarchs]]\n<!-- Honours -->\n[[Category:Grand Crosses of the Order of Saint-Charles]]\n[[Category:Knights Grand Cross of the Order of Saint Joseph]]\n[[Category:Knights Grand Cross of the Military Order of William]]\n[[Category:Knights of the Garter]]\n[[Category:Knights of the Golden Fleece of Spain]]\n[[Category:Grand Crosses of the Order of Saint Stephen of Hungary]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the House Order of Fidelity]]\n[[Category:Knights Grand Cross of the Order of the Z\u00e4hringer Lion]]\n[[Category:Knights of the Order of Saint Hubert]]\n[[Category:Knights Grand Cross of the Royal Guelphic Order]]\n[[Category:Knights Grand Cross of the Ludwigsorden]]\n[[Category:Grand Crosses of the Saxe-Ernestine House Order]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of the White Falcon]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of the Rue Crown]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of St. Andrew]]\n[[Category:Grand Crosses of the Order of the Tower and Sword]]\n[[Category:Grand Crosses of the Order of Christ (Portugal)|3]]\n[[Category:Grand Crosses of the Order of Aviz|3]]\n[[Category:Grand Crosses of the Order of Saint James of the Sword|3]]\n[[Category:Knights Grand Cross of the Order of the Crown (W\u00fcrttemberg)]]\n", "name_user": "2a02:8084:4e61:1c80:a4eb:83d:7742:d943", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(I might have improved it.)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Napoleon_III"}
{"title_page": "Jeff Rupert", "text_new": "'''Jeff Rupert''' (born September 6, 1964)  is a [[Yamaha]] performing artist, a record producer, recording artist, freelance tenor saxophonist, full-time professor, and Director of [[Jazz]] Studies at the [[University of Central Florida]] (UCF).<ref>Yamaha Performing Artists - [http://www.yamaha.com/artists/artistdetailb.html?CNTID=5103049&CTID=5070060 Jeff Rupert]</ref><ref>[http://musicians.allaboutjazz.com/musician.php?id=17343#.UYkAayucVPw Jeff Rupert] - AllAboutJazz.com - D.O.B.</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n*[[Do That Again (album)|Do That Again]] - with [[The Jazz Professors]]  (2013)\n*[[Jazz Town]] with the [[UCF Jazz Ensemble 1]] (2012)\n*[[From Memphis to Mobile]] - Jeff Rupert with [[Kenny Drew, Jr.]] (2009)\n*[[Save Your Love for Me (album)|Save Your Love For Me]] - [[Jeff Rupert + Dirty Martini]] (2004)\n*[[Jeff Rupert (album)|Jeff Rupert]] - self-titled album (2003)\n*[[Superstar (The Fins album)|Superstar]] - [[The Fins]] - [[MAS Records]], (2000)<ref>[http://www.allmusic.com/album/superstar-mw0000106211/credits Superstar] - The Fins - AllMusic</ref>\n*[[Don't Look Back (T-Bone album)|Don't Look Back]] for [[T-Bone (musician)|T-Bone]] [[Orchard Records|Orchard]] (2003)<ref>[http://www.cduniverse.com/search/xx/music/pid/1499579/a/don't+look+back.htm Don't Look Back] - T-Bone [[Orchard Records]] (2000)</ref>\n*[[Harlem Renaissance (album)|Harlem Renaissance]] -for [[Benny Carter]]\n*[[Swingin' for Schuur]] - for [[Diane Schuur]]\n*[[Christmas Songs (Mel Torm\u00e9 album)|Christmas Songs]] for [[Mel Torm\u00e9]]\n*[[The Great American Songbook: Live at Michael's Pub]] for [[Mel Torm\u00e9]]\n\n==Biography==\n\nRupert has been a featured soloist on dozens of recordings with artists like [[Maynard Ferguson]], [[Sam Rivers]], [[Mel Torm\u00e9]], [[Diane Schuur]] and [[Benny Carter]].  He played on Carter's [[Harlem Renaissance]] which won a [[GRAMMY]].  He played with the New Jersey-based Blues band [[The Fins]].<ref>[http://www.allmusic.com/album/superstar-mw0000106211/credits The Fins - Superstar] AllMusic.com</ref> He has also played with [[Kevin Mahogany]], [[Ernestine Anderson]], [[Joe Farnsworth]], [[Ray Drummond]],  pianist [[Benny Green (pianist)|Benny Green]], [[Kenny Drew Jr.]], trumpeter [[Michael Philip Mossman]], and pianist and singer [[Judy Carmichael]].<ref name=\"allaboutjazz\">[http://musicians.allaboutjazz.com/musician.php?id=17343#.UYkAayucVPw Jeff Rupert] - AllAboutJazz.com</ref>\n\nRupert was selected to perform in the [[Jaguar International Jazz Series]] in New Zealand where he worked with [[Joe La Barbera]], [[Larry Koonse]], [[John Fedchock]], and [[Tom Warrington]].<ref name=\"allaboutjazz\" />\n\nHe founded the band [[Jeff Rupert + Dirty Martini]], with which he recorded the [[Bossa]] album \"[[Save Your Love for Me (album)|Save Your Love For Me]]\" (2004).  \"From the moment I first heard Jeff Rupert with my band,\" said Ferguson, \"I considered him one of the great jazz players of today.\"<ref>UCF Music Website - [http://music.cah.ucf.edu/staff.php?id=267 Jeff Rupert Biography]</ref>\n\nHe received his Masters in Jazz Studies from [[Mason Gross School of the Arts]], [[Rutgers University]] in 1993, and his Bachelor of Music in Jazz Studies from [[Mason Gross School of the Arts]] in 1987.\n\nRupert currently is the leader of [[The Jazz Professors]], a sextet which had top [[JazzWeek]] charting hit albums in 2012 and 2013.  \"[[The Jazz Professors: Live at the UCF-Orlando Jazz Festival]]\" (Flying Horse, 2011)  which and peaked at #19 during its seventeen weeks on the JazzWeek charts.  His third album, \"[[From Memphis to Mobile]]\"(CDBY), with [[Kenny Drew, Jr.]]\n\nOn December 6 2013 he appeared and recorded with the [[Happy Feet Jazz Band]] in Brazil on a live album recorded at the Cine Theatro Brasil in Belo Horizonte, Brazil.<ref>[https://www.facebook.com/events/267777033369387/ Happy Feet Jazz Band Live Album Event]</ref>\n\nHe tours with [[Kevin Mahogany]], [[Harry Allen (musician)|Harry Allen]]'s [[Four Others]], [[Ernestine Anderson]], and [[Judy Carmichael]], among others.\n\nRupert joined the [[Sam Rivers Band]] in 1996 and appeared in four recordings with the band.  He has performed in hundreds of appearances with them including performances at [[Lincoln Center]] for [[Ed Bradley's Jazz from Lincoln Center]] (broadcast on NPR), the [[Vision Festival]], NYC and [[Columbia University]].  He has been a member of the [[Jaguar International Jazz Series]] alongside [[Joe La Barbera]], [[Larry Koonse]], [[John Fedchock]], and [[Tom Warrington]].\n\nHe played with [[Ronnie Burrage]] in Band Burrage in 2004.\n\n===As sideman===\nRupert has played for:\n\n*[[Maynard Ferguson]]\n*[[Sam Rivers]]\n*[[Mel Torm\u00e9]]\n*[[Diane Schuur]]\n*[[Benny Carter]]\n*[[Ernestine Anderson]]\n*[[Kevin Mahogany]]\n*[[Benny Green (pianist)|Benny Green]]\n*[[Ray Drummond]]\n*[[Joe Farnsworth]]\n*[[Ronnie Burrage]]\n*[[T-Bone]]\n*[[Kenny Drew Jr.]]\n*[[Judy Carmichael]]\n\n===Major performances===\n\nRupert has performed at:\n\n*[[Alice Tully Hall]]\n*[[Aruba Jazz Festival]], [[Bishopstock]], [[Devon]], [[England]]\n*[[The Blue Note (Missouri)|The Blue Note]]\n*[[Chicago Blues Festival]]\n*The [[Guinness Jazz Festival]], [[Cork (city)|Cork]], [[Ireland]]\n*[[The Jazz Standard]]\n*[[Jamaica Jazz Festival]]\n*[[John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts|The Kennedy Center]]\n*[[Jubileums Blues Festival]], [[Hamar]], [[Norway]]\n*[[Lucerne Jazz Festival]]\n*[[Montreaux Jazz Festival]]\n*[[Pori Jazz Festival]], [[Finland]]\n*[[The Tokyo Forum]]\n\nHe has played at jazz festivals around the world, missing only Africa, to date, with dates in Europe, Scandinavia, Japan, Israel, South America, Australia, and New Zealand.<ref>[http://musicians.allaboutjazz.com/musician.php?id=17343#.UYkYriucVPw Jeff Rupert] - All About Jazz</ref><ref>[http://music.cah.ucf.edu/staff.php?id=267 Jeff Rupert] Faculty Bio - University of Central Florida website</ref>\n\n===As music educator===\n\nAs a full professor and Director of Jazz Studies at the University of Central Florida, Rupert spearheaded a jazz major at UCF, and recruited a top-drawer faculty that includes legendary jazz drummer [[Marty Morell]]. He is the musical director of [[The Flying Horse Big Band]], which began as the [[UCF Jazz Ensemble 1]].  He also runs their Jazz Workshop, teaches a course \"The Evolution of Jazz\" and serves as a private instructor/mentor to selected jazz saxophone students at the university.\n\nRupert is a frequent clinician for festivals, college, high school, and middle school music performance assessments (MPAs) and music education clinics for music educators at events like the [[Florida Music Educators Association]] annual conference in [[Tampa]], [[Florida]].\n\n===As producer===\n\nRupert is the founder of [[Flying Horse Records]], a record label created to promote the talent of both the students and the recording artists in the faculty of the University of Central Florida's Jazz Studies program, and a keystone of the rising Jazz department's mission to make the university's Jazz department a launching point for modern jazz artists.\n\nHe founded and produces the [[UCF Orlando Jazz Festival]], which has been broadcast by [[Dee Dee Bridgewater]] on her [[Jazz Set]] program that appears on Sirius/XM radio and [[NPR]].\n\nHe has produced several records featuring his students in the [[UCF Jazz Ensemble 1]]. Their recording [[Jazz Town]] topped out at 43 on the JazzWeek chart.  [[The Blues Is Alright]], their 2013 release, topped out at 35.<ref>JazzWeek Chart for [http://www.jazzweek.com/charts/1363017600/march-11-2013/ March 11, 2013]</ref>\n\n==References==\n\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rupert, Jeff}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n", "text_old": "'''Jeff Rupert''' (born September 6, 1964)  is a [[Yamaha]] performing artist, a record producer, recording artist, freelance tenor saxophonist, full-time professor, and Director of [[Jazz]] Studies at the [[University of Central Florida]] (UCF).<ref>Yamaha Performing Artists - [http://www.yamaha.com/artists/artistdetailb.html?CNTID=5103049&CTID=5070060 Jeff Rupert]</ref><ref>[http://musicians.allaboutjazz.com/musician.php?id=17343#.UYkAayucVPw Jeff Rupert] - AllAboutJazz.com - D.O.B.</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n*[[Do That Again (album)|Do That Again]] - with [[The Jazz Professors]]  (2013)\n*[[Jazz Town]] with the [[UCF Jazz Ensemble 1]] (2012)\n*[[From Memphis to Mobile]] - Jeff Rupert with [[Kenny Drew, Jr.]] (2009)\n*[[Save Your Love for Me (album)|Save Your Love For Me]] - [[Jeff Rupert + Dirty Martini]] (2004)\n*[[Jeff Rupert (album)|Jeff Rupert]] - self-titled album (2003)\n*[[Superstar (The Fins album)|Superstar]] - [[The Fins]] - [[MAS Records]], (2000)<ref>[http://www.allmusic.com/album/superstar-mw0000106211/credits Superstar] - The Fins - AllMusic</ref>\n*[[Don't Look Back (T-Bone album)|Don't Look Back]] for [[T-Bone (musician)|T-Bone]] [[Orchard Records|Orchard]] (2003)<ref>[http://www.cduniverse.com/search/xx/music/pid/1499579/a/don't+look+back.htm Don't Look Back] - T-Bone [[Orchard Records]] (2000)</ref>\n*[[Harlem Renaissance (album)|Harlem Renaissance]] -for [[Benny Carter]]\n*[[Swingin' for Schuur]] - for [[Diane Schuur]]\n*[[Christmas Songs (Mel Torm\u00e9 album)|Christmas Songs]] for [[Mel Torm\u00e9]]\n*[[The Great American Songbook: Live at Michael's Pub]] for [[Mel Torm\u00e9]]\n\n==Biography==\n\nRupert has been a featured soloist on dozens of recordings with artists like [[Maynard Ferguson]], [[Sam Rivers]], [[Mel Torm\u00e9]], [[Diane Schuur]] and [[Benny Carter]].  He played on Carter's [[Harlem Renaissance]] which won a [[GRAMMY]].  He played with the New Jersey-based Blues band [[The Fins]].<ref>[http://www.allmusic.com/album/superstar-mw0000106211/credits The Fins - Superstar] AllMusic.com</ref> He has also played with [[Kevin Mahogany]], [[Ernestine Anderson]], [[Joe Farnsworth]], [[Ray Drummond]],  pianist [[Benny Green (pianist)|Benny Green]], [[Kenny Drew Jr.]], trumpeter [[Michael Philip Mossman]], and pianist and singer [[Judy Carmichael]].<ref name=\"allaboutjazz\">[http://musicians.allaboutjazz.com/musician.php?id=17343#.UYkAayucVPw Jeff Rupert] - AllAboutJazz.com</ref>\n\nRupert was selected to perform in the [[Jaguar International Jazz Series]] in New Zealand where he worked with [[Joe La Barbera]], [[Larry Koonse]], [[John Fedchock]], and [[Tom Warrington]].<ref name=\"allaboutjazz\" />\n\nHe founded the band [[Jeff Rupert + Dirty Martini]], with which he recorded the [[Bossa]] album \"[[Save Your Love for Me (album)|Save Your Love For Me]]\" (2004).  \"From the moment I first heard Jeff Rupert with my band,\" said Ferguson, \"I considered him one of the great jazz players of today.\"<ref>UCF Music Website - [http://music.cah.ucf.edu/staff.php?id=267 Jeff Rupert Biography]</ref>\n\nHe received his Masters in Jazz Studies from [[Mason Gross School of the Arts]], [[Rutgers University]] in 1993, and his Bachelor of Music in Jazz Studies from [[Mason Gross School of the Arts]] in 1987.\n\nRupert currently is the leader of [[The Jazz Professors]], a sextet which had top [[JazzWeek]] charting hit albums in 2012 and 2013.  \"[[The Jazz Professors: Live at the UCF-Orlando Jazz Festival]]\" (Flying Horse, 2011)  which and peaked at #19 during its seventeen weeks on the JazzWeek charts.  His third album, \"[[From Memphis to Mobile]]\"(CDBY), with [[Kenny Drew, Jr.]]\n\nOn December 6 2013 he appeared and recorded with the [[Happy Feet Jazz Band]] in Brazil on a live album recorded at the Cine Theatro Brasil in Belo Horizonte, Brazil.<ref>[https://www.facebook.com/events/267777033369387/ Happy Feet Jazz Band Live Album Event]</ref>\n\nHe tours with [[Kevin Mahogany]], [[Harry Allen (musician)|Harry Allen]]'s [[Four Others]], [[Ernestine Anderson]], and [[Judy Carmichael]], among others.\n\nRupert joined the [[Sam Rivers Band]] in 1996 and appeared in four recordings with the band.  He has performed in hundreds of appearances with them including performances at [[Lincoln Center]] for [[Ed Bradley's Jazz from Lincoln Center]] (broadcast on NPR), the [[Vision Festival]], NYC and [[Columbia University]].  He has been a member of the [[Jaguar International Jazz Series]] alongside [[Joe La Barbera]], [[Larry Koonse]], [[John Fedchock]], and [[Tom Warrington]].\n\nHe played with [[Ronnie Burrage]] in Band Burrage in 2004.\n\n===As Sideman===\nRupert has played for:\n\n*[[Maynard Ferguson]]\n*[[Sam Rivers]]\n*[[Mel Torm\u00e9]]\n*[[Diane Schuur]]\n*[[Benny Carter]]\n*[[Ernestine Anderson]]\n*[[Kevin Mahogany]]\n*[[Benny Green (pianist)|Benny Green]]\n*[[Ray Drummond]]\n*[[Joe Farnsworth]]\n*[[Ronnie Burrage]]\n*[[T-Bone]]\n*[[Kenny Drew Jr.]]\n*[[Judy Carmichael]]\n\n===Major Performances===\n\nRupert has performed at:\n\n*[[Alice Tully Hall]]\n*[[Aruba Jazz Festival]], [[Bishopstock]], [[Devon]], [[England]]\n*[[The Blue Note (Missouri)|The Blue Note]]\n*[[Chicago Blues Festival]]\n*The [[Guinness Jazz Festival]], [[Cork (city)|Cork]], [[Ireland]]\n*[[The Jazz Standard]]\n*[[Jamaica Jazz Festival]]\n*[[John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts|The Kennedy Center]]\n*[[Jubileums Blues Festival]], [[Hamar]], [[Norway]]\n*[[Lucerne Jazz Festival]]\n*[[Montreaux Jazz Festival]]\n*[[Pori Jazz Festival]], [[Finland]]\n*[[The Tokyo Forum]]\n\nHe has played at jazz festivals around the world, missing only Africa, to date, with dates in Europe, Scandinavia, Japan, Israel, South America, Australia, and New Zealand.<ref>[http://musicians.allaboutjazz.com/musician.php?id=17343#.UYkYriucVPw Jeff Rupert] - All About Jazz</ref><ref>[http://music.cah.ucf.edu/staff.php?id=267 Jeff Rupert] Faculty Bio - University of Central Florida website</ref>\n\n===As Music Educator===\n\nAs a full professor and Director of Jazz Studies at the University of Central Florida, Rupert spearheaded a jazz major at UCF, and recruited a top-drawer faculty that includes legendary jazz drummer [[Marty Morell]]. He is the musical director of [[The Flying Horse Big Band]], which began as the [[UCF Jazz Ensemble 1]].  He also runs their Jazz Workshop, teaches a course \"The Evolution of Jazz\" and serves as a private instructor/mentor to selected jazz saxophone students at the university.\n\nRupert is a frequent clinician for festivals, college, high school, and middle school music performance assessments (MPAs) and music education clinics for music educators at events like the [[Florida Music Educators Association]] annual conference in [[Tampa]], [[Florida]].\n\n===As Producer===\n\nRupert is the founder of [[Flying Horse Records]], a record label created to promote the talent of both the students and the recording artists in the faculty of the University of Central Florida's Jazz Studies program, and a keystone of the rising Jazz department's mission to make the university's Jazz department a launching point for modern jazz artists.\n\nHe founded and produces the [[UCF Orlando Jazz Festival]], which has been broadcast by [[Dee Dee Bridgewater]] on her [[Jazz Set]] program that appears on Sirius/XM radio and [[NPR]].\n\nHe has produced several records featuring his students in the [[UCF Jazz Ensemble 1]]. Their recording [[Jazz Town]] topped out at 43 on the JazzWeek chart.  [[The Blues Is Alright]], their 2013 release, topped out at 35.<ref>JazzWeek Chart for [http://www.jazzweek.com/charts/1363017600/march-11-2013/ March 11, 2013]</ref>\n\n==References==\n\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rupert, Jeff}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n", "name_user": "BuffaloBob", "label": "safe", "comment": "correct headings per MOS: SECTION CAPS", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jeff_Rupert"}
